5000|$|Mellon <b>optical</b> <b>memory</b> was {{an early}} form of {{computer}} memory invented at the Mellon Institute (today part of Carnegie Mellon University) in 1951. The device used a combination of photoemissive and phosphorescent materials to produce a [...] "light loop" [...] between two surfaces. The presence or lack of light, detected by a photocell, represented a one or zero. Although promising, the system was rendered obsolete {{with the introduction of}} core memory in the early 1950s. It appears that the system was never used in production.|$|E
