50|$|Porter {{suggested}} {{using the}} DATAR computer design {{as the basis}} for a sorting system. Following Lewis' suggestion, a new reader would sort the mail {{on the basis of the}} pattern of stripes on the letter provided by an operator who simply typed in the address without attempting to route it. Ferranti suggested a fluorescent ink instead of a conductive one. Routing information would be placed on the magnetic drum, which could store thousands of routes and could be easily changed on demand. Levy, however, was interested in using an <b>optical</b> <b>memory</b> system being developed at IBM by a team including Louis Ridenour (see Automatic Language Translator for details) for storage of the routing information. Turnbull overruled Levy, and on 10 August 1954 he signed a contract with Ferranti for the Electronic Information Handling System using a drum memory.|$|E
